(6150, 1999, 'special_instructions', 'Fumigation\r\nCurrently every FCL container entering Australia (with the exception of groupage boxes) must be fumigated if there are any wooden pallets / skids used, the cargo is packed in crates or if timber bracing is used to secure the load. It is imperative that containers are fumigated overseas before loading on vessels as this is a much cheaper option for importers and reduces unnecessary delays in delivering cargo locally. Fax / email copies of Fumigation Certificates are acceptable and must detail the vessel, container number, number of packages and fumigation treatment used as a minimum requirement.\r\n\r\nThe Australian Quarantine Inspection Service are about to extend this rule to include all LCL shipments and eventually all air freight consignments as well.\r\n\r\nPacking Declarations\r\nEvery FCL container entering Australia (with the exception of groupage boxes) must have a Packing Declaration. This is a standard document that declares whether timber has been used in the packing of the container and that the container was cleaned of dirt and dust prior to loading. The Packing Declaration is to be completed by whoever loads the container i.e. the shipper, the forwarder or a third party warehouse provider. The declaration format must be photocopied on to the packing company\'s letterhead, signed and dated.\r\n\r\nPlease contact us if you require a copy of the Declaration format. '),
